      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the gnome misstep. Let's get down to the nitty-gritty of the interest calculation, no goblin distractions this time.\n\nThe interest on a student loan is typically calculated using the following formula:\n\nInterest = Principal Balance x Interest Rate x Time Period\n\nIn this formula:\n- The Principal Balance is the amount of money you owe on your loan.\n- The Interest Rate is the annual percentage rate (APR) of your loan, which determines how much interest you will accrue each year.\n- The Time Period is usually expressed in a fraction of a year, such as 1/12 for one month.\n\nSo, if you have a $10,000 loan with a 5% annual interest rate, the monthly interest would be calculated as follows:\n\nInterest = $10,000 x 0.05 x (1/12) = $41.67\n\nThis means that each month, $41.67 of interest will be added to your loan balance. When you make a payment, this interest amount is added to the principal balance before you subtract your payment amount. This is why it might feel like the principal isn't going down as fast as you expected, especially when you're just starting out. The interest is added to the",
